    <updated>2023-06-06T06:08:34.648214+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2012-July/001653.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin developers recently engaged in a discussion about the importance of transparency and security in the world of bitcoin development. The conversation was sparked by concerns raised by Amir Taaki regarding the trustworthiness of proprietary software bitcoin clients. Specifically, he questioned the availability of source code for a client on the clients page, suggesting that all clients must have their entire source code available for review.Mats Henricson, another developer, responded to Taaki's inquiry by providing a link to the source code and creating a new section for proprietary clients. However, Gregory Maxwell expressed concerns about the security model of listed software, stating that only thin clients with a near SPV security model should be included on the list.During the discussion, Ben Reeves also requested the inclusion of the blockchain.info iPhone app on the clients page under an lGPL license. Additionally, the conversation touched upon the trustworthiness of proprietary software bitcoin clients and whether or not they should be promoted on the web.The developers also discussed the importance of third-party review and security models when considering whether to list software on the page. They emphasized the need for transparency and security in the world of bitcoin development.In addition to this discussion, the context mentions a live security virtual conference discussing endpoint security, mobile security, and malware threats. Amir Taaki inquired about the source code availability for a different client in a conversation with Harald.</summary>
